lesson.title: Syntax & Data Types
lesson.summary: In this lesson, gain an understanding of how to interact with the R interpreter and the different data types available in R.

atoms.text:
### Summary of What You'll Learn

In this lesson, you will gain knowledge about the fundamentals of working with data in R.

1. You will learn about R data types.
2. You will learn about vectors, and how we can create vectors.
3. You will learn about comparison operators, and how you can use them on vectors and scalars.  
4. You will gain practice with subsetting and logical statements in working with arrays.
5. You will be able to string together logical arguments in your work with 'and' and 'or' statements.
6. You will see a few matrix-specific operations that you can easily compute using R.
7. Finally, you will work hands on with a dataset to understand how to put your skills to work on real data.

Let's get started!

# Jupyter Notebooks

In this program, we'll be using a tool called *Jupyter Notebooks*. Basically, a notebook is a web application that allows you to combine explanatory text, math equations, code, and visualizations all in a single document.

Here's what they look like:

<video loop autoplay style="width: 100%">
<source src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/content.udacity-data.com/courses/ud1111/notebook+interface.mp4" type="video/mp4">
</video>

## Code cells
As you can see in the video above, you can enter code into a cell in the notebook. You can then run that cell (either by clicking the run button as shown above, or by pressing *Shift + Enter*). When you run a code cell, the output will be displayed below the cell.

Notice that you can change the type of any cell to either *Code* cell or *Markdown* cell.

## Markdown cells

Markdown cells are used for displaying explanations, images, equations, and so on, as shown below. Like the name implies, you can use [markdown](https://www.markdownguide.org/) to format the text in these cells.

<video loop autoplay style="width:100%">
<source src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/content.udacity-data.com/courses/ud1111/Markdown+cells.mp4" type="video/mp4">
</video>

# Workspaces
In this program, we'll be running all of the Jupyter Notebooks inside Workspaces here in your classroom, so you don't need to install anything on your computer. Here's a workspace with a Jupyter Notebook inside it, so that you can try it out for yourself:

## ⚠️ Important note
In the lower left corner of your notebook, you'll see there is a **Menu** button. If you click on this, you'll see an option to **Reset Data** (or sometimes **Get New Content**).

If you're having trouble with your workspace or have simply made changes you don't like and want to reset back to the way it was when you started, you can use this option—but **be careful**. Resetting the Workspace means you will lose any code you've been working on. And importantly, each course has a single shared workspace, so **resetting a workspace can reset notebooks on other pages within the same course**.

So if you have code you're working on that you want to save, we recommend that you make a local copy on your computer. You can either copy and paste your code, or you can download your entire notebook by going to **File > Download as**.

# Jupyter Graffiti

Some of the Jupyter notebooks in this course have a special additional feature called **Jupyter Graffiti**. Among other things, Graffiti makes it possible to provide audio walkthroughs of the code provided in the notebook. You'll see an example of a Jupyter Graffiti notebook on the next page, which includes some audio walkthroughs to show you how it works. Be sure to check it out!

Note that some web browsers (including *Brave* and *Safari*) may be unable to handle the audio playback in Graffiti. Try it out on the next page and, if you are unable to hear the walkthrough, then try using [Chrome](https://www.google.com/chrome/) or [Firefox](https://www.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/download/thanks/).

# Graffiti vs. RStudio

In the classroom, we will be using Jupyter Notebooks + Graffiti to introduce new concepts.  Unfortunately, the classroom does not have a built-in RStudio environment.

However, in most industry and academic-related settings RStudio is the standard environment for working with R.  Therefore, you will see RStudio used throughout the videos in this course, but Jupyter Notebooks and Graffiti extension used within the classroom.

On the next page, you can watch me walk through two key concepts in R:

1. Spaces
1. Comments

In order to get started on the next page, you can click on the green underlined text as shown in the image below.

Additionally, you can run any of the cells by clicking **Shift + Enter.**  You can also add your own code, run it, and try out new ideas to see how things work.  

**Note: **This same command works if you would like to run a highlighted portion of code in RStudio.  Simply highlight the code you want to run and press **Shift + Enter.**

#### YOU WON'T BREAK THE CODE, NOTEBOOK, OR CLASSROOM - THIS ENVIRONMENT IS MEANT FOR  YOU TO TEST THINGS AND LEARN FROM THE RESULTS.

# Spaces & Comments

The next page will specifically be on spaces and comments in R.  

For most code you write **Spaces Do Nothing.  **

```undefined
4 + 5
```

and 

```undefined
4 +          5
```

Both of these code blocks produce the result of `9`.

Comments in R can be created with `#` .  Comments are often useful to help others read through your code.  They do not actually run any code that will produce a result.  They are just meant to help guide people through your analysis.  

```undefined
# The below will produce the result 9
# These comments will not be printed as a result
4 + 5 # This is a comment that won't hurt the result, 9 is still printed
```

# Data Types

The first three data types you will need to start using R are 

1. numeric
1. character
1. logicals

On the next page, you will have the ability to get familiar with each of these three data types directly in the classroom.  

You can either 

1. Watch the video to have me guide you through each idea.

2. Run the cells (and even add some) yourself to see the result (Remember **Shift + Return**!)

3. Do some combination of the above.  Remember you can't break anything, so feel free to experiment!

# Numeric

In general, numeric data types include negative and positive numbers.  These include decimal valued numbers as well.  For example, each of the below is an example of a numeric value:

```undefined
5 # this is numeric
5.3 # this is numeric
-12 # this is numeric
-1.2 # this is numeric
```

# Character

Another data type is a character.  Characters are either defined with `'` or `"` quotes around a set of text.  

```undefined
"This is a character" # this is a character
'This is a character' # this is a character
'This is a character" # this is an error - both start and end must match
```

# Logical

Logicals in R must be in **all caps. **They are the values `TRUE` and `FALSE`.  

```undefined
TRUE # this is a logical
True # this is not a logical
```

In order to know what data type something is in R, we can use the keyword `class`.

```undefined
class(TRUE) # returns 'logical'
```

complex_prompt.text: Match each value to the correct data type.

question.prompt:
What is the following data type: 

> "What data type am I"

What is the following data type: 

> 2.4

atoms.text: >*Note*: We won't be using **integer** in this course.  These aren't really useful, except for extreme edge cases.  For most any use case, and for all use cases in this class, you can use a **numerical** data type.

# Vectors

Vectors in R are created with a `c()`.

For example, the below is a vector holding the values 1 through 4.

```undefined
c(1, 2, 3, 4)
```

Vectors can hold any of the data types we have seen so far.  You should be aware that when you have multiple different data types within the same vector, the data types of the individual elements are likely to change.

For example, this will be a vector holding all characters (no surprise here).

```undefined
 c("yes", 'no', "maybe")
```

But you might be surprised to find out that **this will also be a vector holding all characters!!! **

```undefined
 c(1, "no", 2)
```

Each of the numeric values will be converted to a common data type.  Since `"no"` cannot be converted to numeric, **all the numeric values are instead converted to characters **in order to have **all vector elements be of the same data type.**

# rep, seq, and vector

## rep

This repeats values to place in a vector.

```undefined
[Input]:  c(rep(4, times=3), rep(2, times=5))
[Output]: 4 4 4 2 2 2 2 2
```

## seq

This creates a sequence either of some length or with some provided separation between values.

```undefined
[Input]:  seq(1, 10, by=2)
[Output]: 1 3 5 7 9
```

## vector

This provides a vector of a provided number of values with default holders depending on the data type the vector is holding.  For example, a numeric vector of length 5 can be created in the following way.  You can see the **default value for numeric vectors is 0.**

```undefined
[Input]:  vector(mode='numeric', length=5)
[Output]: 0 0 0 0 0
```

For **logical vectors**, the **default value is FALSE.**

While for **character vectors**, the** default value is an empty string.**

## Note:

There are a lot of new items being introduced here.  No one is memorizing that vectors are made using **mode** and **length **as arguments.  These things are items you look up when you need them. You get more familiar with all of these things the more you practice. 

It is important to get comfortable seeing code, and understanding how you might change existing code to solve a new problem you might be introduced to.

In the graffiti notebook on the next page, you will have the opportunity to see three additional commands that are frequently used when creating vectors. You can watch me work through them by clicking the green link on the next page, or you can try running the cells yourself!

# Variables

Variables are created by using an `=` value.  Variables allow us to store the result into a name and then use this result in other places.

For example, I can create the variable `y`

```undefined
y = 4
```

Or I can create the variable `z`

```undefined
z = 5
```

Once these variables are created, I can use them to calculate new values.  For example:

```undefined
[Input]:  y + z
[Output]: 9
[Input]:  y - z
[Output]: -1
[Input]:  y * z
[Output]: 20
[Input]:  y / z
[Output]: 0.8
```

# Variable Naming

Creating names that are informative can help others read your code.  There is always a balance between creating short variable names (that are fast to type) and use variable names that are easy for a reader of your code to understand.

# Comparison Operators

There are a number of comparison operators in R.  Basically anything you can think of!  Below you can see an example of a number of them in comparing our variables `y` and `z`.

```undefined
[Input]:  y = 4 # Create y variable
[Input]:  z = 5 # Create z variable

[Input]:  y > z
[Output]: FALSE

[Input]:  y < z
[Output]: TRUE

[Input]:  y <= z # less than or equal
[Output]: TRUE

[Input]:  y >= z # greater than or equal
[Output]: FALSE

[Input]:  y == z # exactly equal to one another
[Output]: FALSE

[Input]:  y != z # not equal to one another
[Output]: TRUE
```

You can also do these calculations on an entire vector all in one operation!

```undefined
[Input]:  heights = c(67, 74, 63, 70)
[Input]:  heights >= 70 # compares all values in heights to 70
[Output]: FALSE TRUE FALSE TRUE
```

# any, all, which, subset

## any

There are some additional operators that can be quite helpful when working with vectors.

The `any`** **function returns **TRUE **if any of the values in a vector meet some criteria.  For example, the below looks at all items in `heights`  to see if they are less than or equal to 70.  If even one of the values is less than 70, **TRUE **is returned.

In this case, 67, 63, and 70 meet the criteria, so we get a return of `TRUE`.

```undefined
[Input]:  any(heights <= 70)
[Output]: TRUE
```

Alternatively, the following returns `FALSE`, because none of the heights are greater than 80.

```undefined
[Input]:  any(heights > 80)
[Output]: FALSE
```

## all

The `all` command is very similar to the previous command but only returns **TRUE **if all of the elements of a vector meet the provided criteria.  So comparing the two, we can see a case where they differ since not **all **elements in `heights` meet the criteria, but some do. 

```undefined
[Input]:  any(heights <= 70)
[Output]: TRUE
[Input]:  all(heights <= 70)
[Output]: FALSE
```

However, if we change the criteria, we see a new result.

```undefined
[Input]:  all(heights > 60)
[Output]: TRUE
```

## which

The `which` command returns the indices of the vector elements that meet a particular criteria.  **Note that R indexes starting at 1.  **Depending on your experience with other programming languages, you might be used to languages that use 0 i**ndexing - R doesn't do this.**

See below the indices of `heights` that are less than or equal to 70.  We can also pull the values that are exactly equal to 70 or not equal.  

```undefined
[Input]:  which(heights <= 70)
[Output]: 1 3 4
[Input]:  which(heights == 70)
[Output]: 4
[Input]:  which(heights != 70)
[Output]: 1 2 3
```

## subset

The `subset` command works a lot the same way as the `which` command with the largest difference being that a subset command will allow you to pull the indices from other vectors.

For example, if you want to know the eye colors associated with people who are taller than 70 inches, we would use the subset command.

```undefined
# four people with 1st person eye and height in index 1
# 2nd person has eye and height in index 2
# and so on...

[Input]:  eye.colors = c('blue', 'green', 'brown', 'brown')
[Input]:  heights = c(67, 74, 63, 70)

[Input]:  subset(eye.colors, heights > 70)
[Output]: 'green'
```

You can also use `subset` the same way you used `which`, but the above shows a scenario when you might prefer to use this command.

In the graffiti notebook on the next page, you will have the opportunity to see three additional commands that are frequently used when creating vectors. You can watch me work through them by clicking the green link on the next page, or you can try running the cells yourself!

```
     [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4] [,5]
[1,]    1    5    9   13   17
[2,]    2    6   10   14   18
[3,]    3    7   11   15   19

atoms.text: >*Note*: The use of `negative indices` can be useful for a small set of real-world situations, but it is an advanced topic that doesn't get used all that often for most real-world use cases.  If you didn't get that one, no worries.  It wasn't covered in this course, but now you know for next time! If you would like to see more examples of negative indices to drop some elements, please refer to this [blog post](http://www.cookbook-r.com/Basics/Indexing_into_a_data_structure/#negative-indexing).

In the next videos, you will be performing operations on matrices. Below is a refresher. However, if you are totally new to matrix operations, a full course is available at Khan Academy that you may want to consider working through to get comfortable with these and other matrix calculations. # Matrix Manipulation There are a few matrix commands that are useful to understand when working in R. The first is that scalar operations are carried out across all of your matrix elements. If you multiply a matrix by 10, the result is every element of the matrix multiplied by 10. Below you can see an example where I have created `my.array` as a 2x2 matrix. ```undefined [Input]: my.array = array(seq(1,4,1), dim=c(2,2)) [Input]: my.array [Output]: 1 3 2 4 ``` We can then add 10 to all the elements: Therefore the original values change from 1 -> 1 + 10 2 -> 2 + 10 3 -> 3 + 10 4 -> 4 + 10 ```undefined [Input]: my.array + 10 [Output]: 11 13 12 14 ``` We can do the same with multiplication, division, or subtraction. # Transpose The transpose of a matrix flips the values in the rows to instead be in the columns. Below you can see an example of a starting matrix and the result after transposing it. In R it is quite simple to transpose a matrix, as you use the `t()` function. Performing the operation in the image above can be done in the following way: ```undefined [Input]: array1 = array(c(2, -10, 18, 4, 5, -7, -1, 11, 6), dim=c(3,3)) [Input]: t(array1) [Output]: 2 -10 18 4 5 -7 -1 11 6 ``` # Matrix Multiplication You can also do matrix multiplication easily in R. A couple of reminders about matrix multiplication 1. The number of columns in the first matrix must equal the number of columns in the second matrix. 1. The value in the final matrix for any position is equal to the dot product of the row in the first matrix with the column in the second matrix. You can see this in the image below. In order to complete the **matrix multiplication** shown in the image above in R, we perform use the operator `%*%`: ```undefined [Input]: array1 = array(c(1, 3, 2, 4), dim=c(2,2)) [Input]: array2 = array(c(5, 0, 6, 7), dim=c(2,2)) [Input]: array1 %*% array2 [Output]: 5 20 15 46 ``` You can see that we first list all the elements in the first column followed by the elements in the second column. This pattern would continue no matter the number of rows or columns in our matrix. # cbind & rbind The `cbind` and `rbind` commands are useful for adding columns or rows to existing matrices or creating new matrices! You can see an example in the image below. As a reminder, you can pull a particular row of any matrice using square brackets. Consider the below, as this will be useful for a couple of the quizzes ahead! We can create a matrix and pull the first row using `[1, ]` ```undefined [Input]: array1 = array(c(1, -3, 0, 2), dim=c(2,2)) [Input]: array1[1, ] # pulls the first row [Output]: 1 0 ``` We can pull say the third column of a matrix with `[ ,3]` ```undefined [Input]: array1[ ,1] # pulls the first column [Output]: 1 -3 ``` We can bind the results either on columns ```undefined [Input]: cbind(array1[ ,1], array1[1, ]) # [Output]: 1 1 -3 0 ``` or the rows ```undefined [Input]: rbind(array1[ ,1], array1[1, ]) # [Output]: 1 -3 1 0 ``` Pretty cool, right! # Your Turn In the notebook on the next page, you will have the opportunity to try out this yourself! Then you will test your skills with a few problems. If you aren't sure of a result by hand, you can always use R to calculate the result - that's what the computer is for!

#### Remember

You can click any text in the graffiti notebooks in order to see my walkthrough videos. You also can change code, add new cells, and run existing cells by clicking **Shift + Return**.  This will allow you to test out ideas yourself!  **This is the best way to get comfortable in R.**

atoms.text:
# Iris Dataset

As we wrap up this first lesson, let's look at a few commands that are really common when working with a new data type called **'data.frame'.  **This is one of the most common data types used in R in the "real world", as it looks just like spreadsheet data you might have seen in applications like excel, google sheets, or other row-column based applications.

For getting started, we will look at the **Iris **dataset.  A snippet of this dataset is shown below.

You can see the `head()` command is used to look at the first few rows of the dataset.  You can specify exactly how many rows you want to look at by providing a second argument.  

For example, to look at the first 3 rows of the dataset, you can use: 

```undefined
head(iris, 3)
```

Let's consider some additional popular commands

# Working with Data Frames Cheat Sheet

**1. head(iris, 7)**  - returns top 7 rows of the dataframe

**2. tail(iris, 3) ** - returns last 3 rows of the dataframe

**3. dim(iris)   - ** returns the number of rows and columns in the dataframe

**4. summary(iris)  - **returns all the summary statistics for every column in the dataframe

**5. iris$Sepal.Length - **returns the Sepal.Length column (we can do this with any column and the $)

**6. min(iris$Sepal.Length) - **returns the min value in the Sepal.Length column

There are similar functions **mean(), max(), median(), sd(), etc.**

**7. subset(iris, Species=='virginica' & Petal.Length > 5) **- returns rows meeting these criteria



**Note: **Dataframes in R, are very much like the arrays you have already been working with.  One of the main ways you can notice this is in indexing.

If you would like the first row of the iris dataframe, you can pull this row using:

```undefined
iris[1, ]
```

You can also pull the first 7 values in the Sepal.Length column using:

```undefined
iris$Sepal.Length[1:7]
```

Notice, this is pulling the full column, but then we are subsetting further to only the first 7 values.  The key takeaway here is that the **same row, column indexing you have been using can be used directly with data.frames**.

# Note Before Starting Next Quizzes

The last parts of this lesson are moving into an area where there isn't always one right answer.  With that being said, there are few reminders worth sharing at this point.

**1. **In the quizzes and solutions you see on the next two pages, you will be asked a number of **questions that could be solved a number of different ways.  **

**2. It isn't cheating to look back at your notes.  **Coding is not a game of memorization.

**3. It isn't cheating to copy code from the classroom and update it to get a solution.**

**4. It isn't cheating to use the classroom workspace or RStudio to test your solutions.**

Most problems in the real world, you probably won't know the answer right away.  In this lesson, you are picking up the skills that you can start to piece together to get solutions.  **You don't need to know the answer right away or have it memorized to put in the box to be a success.  Success is about learning from your mistakes and not being afraid to revisit the same ideas over and over again until they make sense.**

With that, the next quiz questions can be challenging for many.  Don't fret if you don't get them on your first try.  It is awesome that you have made it this far! Learning to program in a new language is no easy task!

atoms.text:
### Recap

In this lesson, you learned a ton about working with data in R.

1. You learned about data types including 
```
     a. numeric
     b. character
     c. logical 
```
2. You learned about vectors, and how we can create vectors using 
```
     a. vector()
     b. seq()
     c. c()
```
3. You learned about comparison operators, and how you can use them on vectors and scalars.  These included:
```
  a. > (greater than)
  b. < (less than)
  c. <= (less than or equal)
  d. >= (greater than or equal)
  e. == (equal)
  f. != (not equal)
```
4.  Then you learned how to subset arrays using indexing and square brackets.  A few examples include:
```
  a. subset(array, array > 5) (only elements greater than 5) 
  b. array[c(1,3), 1:5] (first and third row, columns 1-5)
  c. array[1,2] (only the element in the first row, second column)
```
5. You also learned about how to combine arguments:
```
  a.  a > 5 & b < 7 (and)
  b. a > 5 || b < 7 (or)
```
6. You learned about a few matrix operations.  These included:
```
  a. %*% (matrix multiplication)
  b. t(array) (transpose)
  c. *, +, - . / (scalar operations you can perform on an array)
  d. cbind(array1, array2) (combining columns into a single array)
  e. rbind(array1, array2) (combining rows into a single array)
```
7. Finally, we looked at the `iris` dataset, which was a `data.frame`.  You learned about additional operations on dataframes.  A few of these operations include:
```
  a. head(df, 7) (show top 7 rows, tail works similarly)
  b. dim(df) (gives row, column of the dataframe)
  c. summary(df) (gives summary statistics on each column)
  d. min(df$col) (gives min of this column in the dataframe) 
  e. max(), sd(), mean(), median() (additional statistics you can calculate)
```
You now have a ton of operations you can use to work with data in R! Nice work!
